@* ============================================================
   RulesContent.razor — the rule, in HTML, for the player.
   Source: src/UpAllNight.App/Shared/RulesContent.razor
   ============================================================

   This is the third of three surfaces the meld rule lives on.
   The same .razor body is rendered by both the in-game rules
   modal AND the /how-to-play page. Two consumers, one source.

   The audience: a player who has thirty seconds before they
   tap "got it" and go back to the game. The vocabulary is the
   plainest of the three (no "BookType.Natural", no
   "@Reason IN (1,2,3)") — just <strong> tags around the words
   that matter and a structure that's scannable, not exhaustive.

   The two lines that changed when the meld rule was wrong:
    - "You may start a 2nd book of the same rank in the
      OPPOSITE type." (Was: had to match.)
    - "Tap an existing book to lay off cards onto it — even
      a completed one, for extra scoring." (Was: completed
      books were locked.)

   The modal is the loudest of the three surfaces when it lies,
   because it's the rule the player just read fifteen seconds
   ago. Get the modal wrong, and the player taps a move the
   modal just told them was legal, hits a refusal, and concludes
   the game is broken.

   Companion rules:
    - MeldService.ValidateMeld (sample 01)
    - docs/gamerules.md (sample 02)
   ============================================================
*@

<section class="rules-section">
    <h2>Your Turn</h2>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Draw:</strong> either take 2 cards from the draw pile, or take the top 5 from the discard pile.</li>
        <li><strong>Meld:</strong> play cards into new or existing books. Tap an existing book to lay off cards onto it — even a completed one, for extra scoring.</li>
        <li><strong>Discard:</strong> end your turn by placing one card on the discard pile.</li>
    </ol>
</section>

<section class="rules-section">
    <h2>Books — Natural vs. Dirty</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>A <strong>natural</strong> book is 7 cards of the same rank with <em>no</em> wilds. A <strong>dirty</strong> book is 7 cards of the same rank that includes at least one wild (Joker or 2).</li>
        <li>You may start a 2nd book of the same rank in the <strong>opposite</strong> type — e.g. close a natural 7s book and then start a dirty 7s book. A new dirty book must include at least one wild on its first meld.</li>
        <li>While a natural book is still incomplete, you may add a wild to convert it into a dirty book — but only if your team doesn't already have a dirty book of that rank.</li>
        <li>Once a natural book is <strong>completed</strong>, its type is locked: you can keep adding matching naturals for points, but no wilds.</li>
        <li>Completed dirty books also accept lay-offs for additional scoring.</li>
    </ul>
</section>
